[2]
Date: 14 Apr 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: AFP via Yahoo News Canada, 9 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&cid=1526&ncid=1526&e=5&u=/afp/20040409/wl_canada_afp/canada_health_flu_animal_040409205325>


Owners of Parrots and Pigeons Seek Stay of Execution in Canada
Bird Cull
-----------------------------------------------
Exotic bird owners are crying foul, as parrots, racing pigeons,
budgies, fancy hens, and ostriches are threatened by an order to
cull 19 million poultry in order to stamp out avian flu in western
Canada. "It's absolutely foolish, because these birds are all
endangered species, and you can't just go around hacking them to
death," said Wendy Huntbatch, president of For the Love of
Parrots rescue society.

The cull of turkeys, ducks, chickens and other birds was ordered on
Mon 12 Apr 2004, in a bid to halt the spread of highly contagious
bird-flu, which has now been found on 20 poultry farms. Exotic bird
owners say they will fight to have their birds excluded from the
execution order, arguing that it is over the top.

"The chance of the virus passing to parrots is very remote," said
Huntbatch, who looks after 400 parrots. "We've retained a lawyer,
and we'll fight them tooth and nail. There is no way I'll let (officials)
on my property," she said, pledging to block her gates with hundreds
of supporters from across North America.

Local racing pigeon owners have also hired a lawyer to defend
their 50 000 pigeons worth CAD 25 to 17 000 [USD 19 to 12 900]
each, some that have raced home from as far away as Alberta or
California in competitions. "The decision is totally unfair. We've got
documentation from vets that pigeons don't get this disease," said
Trey Coulson of the North Road Racing Pigeon Society which
represents over 200 pigeon owners who plan to lock down their
birds until the disease threat has passed.

Officials will consider exemptions if owners can prove that their
birds are not at risk of contracting and spreading avian influenza,
but say a billion-dollar poultry industry is at stake, and the
bird-flu must be contained.

"[We are] going to approach these specialty birds with an
abundance of caution and make sure that none of these birds
could possibly be harboring avian influenza virus and, down the
road, be a potential source of a future outbreak," said Cornelius
Kiley, of the Canadian Food Inspection Agency.

Family pets kept indoors will not be put down, he said.

